The game received mostly positive reviews upon release. John Highcliffe of ''The Games Machine'' praised the historical accuracy of the game, stating that gamers with an interest with the era would enjoy the game. However, Highcliffe expressed concern over the slow pace of the game.<ref name=john>{{cite journal|last1=Highcliffe|first1=John|title=Austerlitz review|journal=The Games Machine|date=March 1990|issue=28|page=87|url=https://archive.org/stream/the-games-machine-28/TheGamesMachine28#page/n86/mode/1up|access-date=16 January 2016}}</ref> Alain Huyghes-Lacour of ''Tilt'' praised the game's graphics and 3D presentation of the battle, stating that it exceeded the benchmark set by other wargames.<ref name=tilt>{{cite journal|last1=Huyghes-Lacour|first1=Alain|title=Austerlitz review (Tilt)|journal=Tilt|date=March 1990|issue=76|page=80|url=http://download.abandonware.org/magazines/Tilt/tilt_numero076/TILT%20076%20-%20Page%20080%20(1990-03).JPG|access-date=16 January 2016|language=French}}</ref> Mark Higham of ''[[ST Format]]'' questioned the historical accuracy, stating that during the real battle French forces used smoke grenades frequently, and criticised the lack of this inclusion in the game. However, Higham heralded the game as the best, saying that there is "no other wargame like it".<ref name=ST>{{cite journal|last1=Higham|first1=Mark|title=Austerlitz review|journal=ST Format|date=April 1989|issue=8|pages=48, 49|url=http://www.stformat.com/stf08/index.html|access-date=16 January 2016}}</ref>

Mark Patterson of ''[[ACE (magazine)|ACE]]'' praised the smooth animation and impressive graphics; however, he criticised the game's lack of sound as uninspiring.<ref name=ace>{{cite journal|last1=Patterson|first1=Mark|title=Austerlitz review|journal=ACE|date=March 1990|issue=30|page=40|url=https://archive.org/stream/ace-magazine-30/ACE_Issue_30_1990_Mar#page/n39/mode/1up|access-date=16 January 2016}}</ref> Higham considered ''Austerlitz'' superior to other games released by the developer, suggesting that it offered a higher state of realism.<ref name=ST/> Lucinda Orr of ''[[Amiga Computing]]'' stated that the graphics were "wonderful" and opinionated that the game was the best Napoleon warfare simulation of its kind.<ref name="AC">{{cite journal|last1=Orr|first1=Lucinda|title=Austerlitz: War without tears|journal=Amiga Computing|date=April 1990|volume=2|issue=11|pages=40, 41}}</ref> A reviewer of ''[[Amiga Format]]'' said that the 3D graphics were "great", but declared that the lack of sound was the "last thing" a player would need in a serious wargame.<ref name="AF">{{cite journal|title=Austerlitz review|journal=Amiga Format|date=March 1990|issue=8|page=53|url=https://archive.org/stream/amigaformatmagazine-008/Amiga_Format_Issue_008_1990_03_Future_Publishing_GB#page/n51/mode/2up/search/austerlitz|access-date=3 February 2016}}</ref> Jonathan Davies of ''[[Amiga Power]]'' praised the graphics as the only "plus side" aspect of the game, however he criticised the slow pace of gameplay, stating that it would take hours and a lot of patience to type out orders.<ref name="AP">{{cite journal|last1=Davies|first1=Jonathan|title=Austerlitz (Amiga Power)|journal=Amiga Power|date=January 1991|issue=9|url=https://archive.org/stream/Amiga_Power_Issue_09_1992-01_Future_Publishing_GB#page/n101/mode/2up/search/austerlitz|access-date=3 February 2016}}</ref> A reviewer of ''Australian Commodore and Amiga review'' asserted that ''Austerlitz'' was designed for serious gamers, stating that the complexity of the game would make "seasoned wargamers happy as pigs in mud".<ref name="aus">{{cite journal|title=Mind Games: Austerlitz|journal=Australia Commodore and Amiga Review|date=February 1991|volume=8|issue=2|page=75|url=https://archive.org/stream/Australian_Commodore_and_Amiga_Review_The_Volume_8_Issue_2_1991-02_Saturday_Magazine_AU#page/n73/mode/2up/search/austerlitz|access-date=3 February 2016}}</ref>

